size(250);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

triple A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H, I, J, K, L;

A = (8,1,-7);
B = (9,1,-7);
C = (9,0,-7);
D = (8,0,-7);
E = A + (0,0,1);
F = B + (0,0,1);
G = C + (0,0,1);
H = D + (0,0,1);
I = A + (0,1,0);
J = B + (0,1,0);
K = C + (0,1,0);
L = D + (0,1,0);

draw(E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(I--J--K--L--cycle);
draw(E--I);
draw((5.5,0.5,-6.5)--(6.5,0.5,-6.5),Arrow3(6));
draw((5.5,0.5,-6.5)--(5.5,1.5,-6.5),Arrow3(6));
draw((8.5,0.5,-6.5)--(7.5,0.5,-6.5),Arrow3(6));
[/asy]

The projection of the trapezoid onto the $xy$-plane is as shown above.  Let $AC=x$ and $DF=y$.  Then the maximization of area is the maximization of $A(x,y)$ over $x,y\geq 0$.  Note that by similarity,
\[\frac{x}{4} = \frac{25-4x}{7},\]
so $x=\frac{100}{33}$.  Moreover, the hypotenuse of the right triangle below is $\sqrt{1^2+7^2}=\sqrt{50}$, so by the Pythagorean Theorem $y=\frac{16}{3}$.  The areas of these two right triangles are $\frac{10}{33}$ and $\frac{16}{3}$, respectively, so the maximal area of the trapezoid is $\boxed{\frac{524}{99}}$ square units.

